Local Engagement as an Antidote against Populism
PARIS – The parties that once dominated Western democracies in their core have been shaken.
Many – including France, Italy, Greece, and the United Kingdom – have suffered crushing election defeats.
Others have changed so drastically that only the name has remained.
The Republican Party of US President Donald Trump has little in common with that of former President Ronald Reagan.
These developments are similar everywhere in the West.
The leadership of the formerly dominant parties oscillates between denial and desperation, while populists fish for their traditional followers.
Some refuse to recognize a legitimate reason for their defeat, and dismiss their supporters as 'pitiful' to their opponents, just like Hillary Clinton did, shortly before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are too scared by the populist tide to launch a counterattack.
Neither denial nor self-satisfaction will resolve the entrenched political situation.
The Progressives must reorganize themselves, and this begins with a diagnosis of the inadequacies of the traditional parties.
A part of the problem is that the traditional parties have not recognized the true themes of our time.
Still trapped on the old ideological battlefields, they ignored the decreasing social mobility, the intensifying environmental crises, the increasing geographical inequality, the tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other issues that actually concern the voters.
They were the avant-garde decades ago.
Today, they are all alone in the woods, wondering where everyone has gone.
The social sciences could have an answer as to why the mainstream has strayed from the path.
The gap between their objective analysis of reality and the policies of governments has widened into a chasm.
In most Western countries, economists have been aware for a long time of the growing gap in income and other indicators between some prosperous cities that benefit from globalization and the rest of the country.
However, until the government of French President Emmanuel Macron did so, no national head of government had implemented tax cuts based on residence.
As a result of this policy, 1% of the French GDP is now primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
Traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to voters rather than only through the filters of the media and opinion research institutes.
In the year 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! started with the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What voters told the inquirers was then the basis of Macron's presidential election campaign.
For example, „La Grande Marche“ had collected numerous statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's allegedly sexual advances towards women, and Macron promised to deal with the problem in case of his election.
At the time, Macron's stance made him the target of jokes from his opponents; however, their laughter quickly faded with the advent of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not enough.
Traditional parties also suffer from poor organization.
They long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections where activists occasionally hand out flyers and cheer for the candidates.
This was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that views democracy as a marketplace consisting of government providers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this view, the sole purpose of a party is to seize and maintain power.
It is no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, established parties had a number of advantages that delayed their collapse.
Over the past years they had a technological lead against less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups that could mobilize people to elections, organize protests, and start petitions.
But this model no longer applies.
Citizens refuse today to be mere consumers of state policy.
Along with a higher level of education, new demands for participation arose.
The voters want to be treated as political actors of their own right and not as pawns in the game of others.
Furthermore, governments are no longer the only providers of political measures themselves.
This is one of the harsh lessons we had to learn in the two years we worked alongside Macron in the Élysée Palace.
The most important political challenges today – climate change, religious extremism, digital upheavals, and gender equality – cannot be solved by national governments alone.
These challenges require profound cultural changes and, in most cases, measures on a sub- and supranational level.
And finally, technology has lowered the barriers to political participation, so that traditional parties can no longer rely on the incumbent bonus and consolidated support networks.
Anyone who can handle Google, Twitter, and Facebook well, does not need a century-old party apparatus.
Political movements need to be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures and not just on elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an administrative "back office"; the front office should be occupied by people on the ground.
At La République En Marche! we refer to this as local citizen projects.
These can range from literacy classes after school and integration programs for immigrants to cooperative vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
In any case, it is about offering tailor-made solutions for local problems and thus strengthening the community.
One should consider such projects today as indispensable complements to state politics.
In the future, a party's ability to offer worthwhile paths for political and community engagement will be crucial for its appeal.
And by presenting their reform policies "live" every day, the parties have already prepared the ground for success on election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what is being said, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the hard lesson that the traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can win people over to their side.
Restoring the connection to voters' concerns, therefore, goes hand in hand with adapting party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need progressive local politics.
